issue.title: Error Message String Contains [object Object]
issue.body:
I'm currently working on the PR generated by https://github.com/sanctuary-js/sanctuary/issues/291. The new implementation of `pluck` looks like this:

```js
def('pluck',
      {a: [Accessible]},
      [$.String, $.Array({a: [Accessible]}), $.Array(a)],
      pluck);
```

Unfortunately it seems that `sanctuary-def` can't handle `$.Array({a: [Accessible]})`:

```
TypeError: Invalid value

pluck :: Accessible a => String -> Array [object Object] -> Array a
                         ^^^^^^
                           1
```

const {app, BrowserWindow} = require('electron')

// handle squirrel events:
// https://github.com/electron/grunt-electron-installer#handling-squirrel-events
if(require('electron-squirrel-startup')) return;

let win

const installExtenstions = () => {
  const installer = require('electron-devtools-installer');
  require('electron-debug')({showDevTools: true});

  const extensions = [
    'REACT_DEVELOPER_TOOLS',
    'REDUX_DEVTOOLS'
  ];
  for (const name of extensions) {
    try {
      installer.default(installer[name]);
    } catch (e) {}
  }
}

function createWindow () {

  win = new BrowserWindow({width: 800, height: 600})

  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development') {
    installExtenstions()
    win.webContents.openDevTools()
    win.loadURL('http://localhost:3000/')
  } else {
    win.loadURL(`file://${__dirname}/index.html`)
  }


  win.on('closed', () => {
    win = null
  })
}

app.on('ready', createWindow)

app.on('window-all-closed', () => {
  if (process.platform !== 'darwin') {
    app.quit()
  }
})

app.on('activate', () => {
  if (win === null) {
    createWindow()
  }
})

issue.body:
This script fails:

```
#!/usr/bin/env python

from intermine.webservice import Service
service = Service("http://intermine.wormbase.org/tools/wormmine/service")
query = service.new_query("Gene")
query.add_view(
    "symbol", "secondaryIdentifier", "expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"
)
query.add_sort_order("Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier", "ASC")
for row in query.rows():
    print row["symbol"], row["secondaryIdentifier"], row["expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier"], \
        row["expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name"], \
        row["expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"]
```

But works on the site: http://intermine.wormbase.org/tools/wormmine/template.do?name=show_expression_of_a_given_gene Returns 2 million+ records. Maybe that's the issue?

@tharris What is the error message in the Tomcat logs? I can't reproduce this issue in FlyMine.

@justinccdev Can you coordinate with Todd to fix this issue in WormMine? The query works on the site so has to be a client issue. Do you think? However, I can run a query (return all proteins and genes, 5 million+ records) on beta flymine and it works just fine. Maybe because only one table?

Also an issue in Yeastmine. Can you help @kkarra fix? http://yeastmine.yeastgenome.org/yeastmine/template.do?name=Gene_SpellExpressionScores

comment.body:
Okay, I still believe that the root problem is the query time mis-estimation issue in InterMine (which may or may not be fixable at root if we are relying on inaccurate PostgreSQL estimations).

However, the proximal reason is that the Python and Perl libraries do generate different webservice requests.  From capturing outgoing HTTP traffic for the queries above, it turns out that the Perl library generates the query

http://intermine.wormbase.org/tools/wormmine/service/query/results?query=%3Cquery%20model%3D%22genomic%22%20name%3D%22%22%20sortOrder%3D%22Gene.symbol%20asc%20Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier%20asc%22%20view%3D%22Gene.symbol%20Gene.secondaryIdentifier%20Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier%20Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name%20Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym%22%2F%3E&format=json

(decoded)

query=<query model="genomic" name="" sortOrder="Gene.symbol asc Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier asc" view="Gene.symbol Gene.secondaryIdentifier Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"/>&format=json

whilst the Python library generates the query

http://intermine.wormbase.org/tools/wormmine/service/query/results?query=%3Cquery+longDescription%3D%22%22+model%3D%22genomic%22+name%3D%22%22+sortOrder%3D%22Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier+asc%22+view%3D%22Gene.briefDescription+Gene.description+Gene.id+Gene.lastUpdated+Gene.length+Gene.name+Gene.operon+Gene.primaryIdentifier+Gene.score+Gene.scoreType+Gene.secondaryIdentifier+Gene.symbol+Gene.symbol+Gene.secondaryIdentifier+Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier+Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name+Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym%22%2F%3E&format=json

(decoded)

query=<query longDescription="" model="genomic" name="" sortOrder="Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier asc" view="Gene.briefDescription Gene.description Gene.id Gene.lastUpdated Gene.length Gene.name Gene.operon Gene.primaryIdentifier Gene.score Gene.scoreType Gene.secondaryIdentifier Gene.symbol Gene.symbol Gene.secondaryIdentifier Gene.expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name Gene.expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"/>&start=0&format=json

The 2 differences are:

* The Perl library adds "Gene.symbol asc" to the sort order
* The Python library adds "Gene.briefDescription Gene.description Gene.id Gene.lastUpdated Gene.length Gene.operon Gene.score Gene.scoreType" to the view.

The Perl addition turns out not to be important.  However, it looks like the Python addition is enough to trigger the mis-estimation of the query time and the timeout.  Manually eliminating the extra selected columns from the HTTP request allows it to work.  Adding certain columns back to the request triggers the failure (e.g. adding Gene.description and Gene.briefDescription separately is fine, but adding both triggers the 500 failure).

What is making Python add the extra columns, even though we don't request them in a view?  From code inspection, on the

```query = service.new_query("Gene")```

call, the Python library automatically adds all the class view columns, both from Gene itself and its parent classes (hence name, description, briefDescription, etc.).  In fact, in the original python script you can replace 

```
query.add_view(
    "symbol", "secondaryIdentifier", "expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"
)
```

with 

query.select(
    "symbol", "secondaryIdentifier", "expressionPatterns.primaryIdentifier",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.name",
    "expressionPatterns.lifeStages.anatomyTerms.synonym"
)

and it will work just fine, since select() removes the existing columns rather than adding to them.

Why is Python adding these columns even though we don't appear to need them?  I don't know, that may be a question for @alexkalderimis.  We could stop the Python library from doing this but that might affect existing scripts that rely on this behaviour.  The simplest solution here, even if not very satisfactory, may be to put a much bigger query estimation limit in InterMine by default, or perhaps try and fix the root cause of the mis-estimation, though I'm not optimistic that's realistically possible as it looks like the root cause may be in Postgres itself.

This request may also apply to other `NodeFactory` implementations, but so far I have only been using the `ByteArrayNodeFactory` and `CharArrayNodeFactory` implementations.

In my use case I build a tree for 1.5M+ mappings resulting in a RadixTree with 1.9M+ nodes. Of these nodes more than 33% have an incoming edge containing only a single character. Wrapping that single byte (or char) in an array incurs a rather big overhead: 4 bytes for the reference + 16 bytes for the array (12 object overhead, 1 byte payload, 3 bytes of padding). So a total of 20 bytes vs. a single byte (or two bytes for `CharArrayNodeFactory`). Depending on the padding required for the concrete node implementation I suppose one could save between 16 and 20 bytes of memory, when dealing with nodes with a single character in the incoming edge. For my particular tree that makes quite a difference.

Since I can supply my own `NodeFactory` implementation I can of course extend the mentioned implementations accordingly. I was just wondering if this improvement may be of general interest.

From the specification:
It would be useful if there was a way to make some columns standard and some additional – i.e. columns that could be expanded/selected if required (e.g. sensitivity*). It would, however, be good if the underlying code was flexible, in that the status of columns (i.e. standard or additional) might change over time and between websites. Columns would be selected from a standard list (i.e. user-specified columns are not allowed).

issue.title: Spring boot Embedded tomcat Performance Improvements
issue.body:
In apache tomcat uses apache portable runtime(APR) to provide better performance and scalability with native execution. APR uses system resources and execute natively. If we compare the execution performance BIO , NIO and APR connectors APR provides superior performance.

I have experience the same in my development phase. I created two sets of artifacts which is standalone Jar with spring boot  embedded tomcat and spring boot war file and deployed on "tomcat" both are same code base but APR configuration is only difference.

Spring boot by default all the threads execution based on “NIO”, so I have compiled APR libraries based on below link:-

https://tomcat.apache.org/tomcat-8.0-doc/apr.html

Executed Spring Boot Jar file with APR.  Now I can see performance results are exactly same.

**In our spring boot documentation does not have APR guide to add in embedded tomcat. If we add it will help other developers as well.**
